%I A397790 #21 Jul 20 2026 00:43:48
%S A397790 9,25,121,361,1369,2209,5041,6889,11881,24649,29929,51529,69169,78961,
%T A397790 100489,146689,208849,229441,299209,358801,383161,491401,573049,
%U A397790 703921,908209,1026169,1100401,1229881,1274641,1442401,2053489,2247001,2563201,2679769
%N A397790 a(n) = prime^2 closest to prime(n)^3.
%C A397790 a(n) = 1 (mod 24) for any n >= 2 because the nearest prime q is always >= 5 and the square of any prime q >= 5 is of the form 24k + 1.
%C A397790 Empirically, the closest prime square to prime(n)^3 is always unique. It's conjectured that no tie occurs.
%C A397790 The distance a(n) - prime(n)^3 is asymptotically bounded by O(p^1.5 * log(p)).
%C A397790 A tie cannot occur: Suppose that p^2 + q^2 = 2*r^3 for p, q, r >= 5 primes, then r == 1 (mod 24), and so r can be written as a+b*i with a > b > 0. It is clear that gcd(p+q*i, p-q*i) = 1+i in the ring of Gaussian integers, so one of p+q*i and p-q*i must be associated to (a+b*i)^3*(1+i) and the other to (a-b*i)^3*(1+i). By comparing the real and imaginary parts, one of p and q is equal to |(a+b)*(a^2-4*a*b+b^2)| and the other to |(a-b)*(a^2+4*a*b+b^2)|. This implies that we have both a^2 - 4*a*b + b^2 = +-1 and a - b = 1, which is impossible. - _Jianing Song_, Jul 13 2026
%H A397790 James C. McMahon, <a href="/A397790/b397790.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A397790 Conjecture: a(n) = A397789(n)^2. [In other words, it is conjectured that there are no consecutive primes p1 < p2 and a prime q such that (p1 + p2)^2/4 < q^3 < (p1^2 + p2^2)/2. - _Jianing Song_, Jul 14 2026]
%e A397790 Prime(2)^3 = 3^3 = 27. Prime 5^2 = 25, so a(2) = 25.
%t A397790 a[n_]:=Nearest[{NextPrime[Prime[n]^1.5,-1]^2,NextPrime[Prime[n]^1.5]^2},Prime[n]^3][[1]];Array[a,34]
%Y A397790 Cf. A000040, A001248, A002821, A030078, A077118, A397789.
%K A397790 nonn,new
%O A397790 1,1
